Why Jerome Powell must go
NEW YORK – US President Joe Biden is facing a critical decision: Who should he appoint as the head of the US Federal Reserve – possibly the most powerful position within the global economy?
A wrong decision here can have grave consequences.
Under Alan Greenspan and Ben Bernanke, the Fed failed to properly regulate the banking system, thus laying the groundwork for the worst global economic downturn in 75 years.
This crisis and the political decision-makers' response to it had far-reaching political consequences; they exacerbated inequality and fostered a lasting sense of discontent among those who lost their homes and jobs.
There are a variety of clichés as to why the current central bank chief Jerome Powell should be reappointed.
It would be a proof of bipartisanship.
It would strengthen the credibility of the Fed.
We need someone with experience who can lead us through the recovery following the pandemic.
And so on.
I have heard the same arguments exactly 25 years ago when I was the chairman of the economic advisory staff of US President Bill Clinton and the confirmation of Greenspan in office was an issue.
They were enough to convince Clinton, and the country paid dearly for his decision.
Ironically, President Ronald Reagan paid little attention to these arguments when he effectively fired Paul Volcker in 1987 and Volcker, after having curbed inflation, was denied a second term.
Reagan owed a lot to Volcker, but he sought deregulation and therefore chose Greenspan, an Ayn Rand follower.
In economic policy, careful evaluation and sensitivity to conflict of goals are needed.
How important is inflation compared to jobs and growth?
How confident can we be that markets are efficient, stable, fair, and driven by competition on their own?
How concerned should we be about inequality?
The two major parties in the US have always held distinctly different, yet clearly articulated views on these issues (at least until the Republicans gave in to populist fervor).
From my perspective, Democrats are rightly concerned about the consequences of unemployment.
The 2008 crisis has shown that unregulated markets are neither efficient nor stable.
Furthermore, we know that traditionally, only in times of tight labor markets are marginalized groups incorporated into the economy and wage disparities reduced.
The coming years will be a test for every US Federal Reserve Chairman.
Already, the US is facing difficult decisions about what to do about inflation.
Are the recent price increases essentially minor problems that arise from an unprecedented economic shutdown?
How should the Fed consider the unemployment rate among African Americans, which has still not recovered to its pre-pandemic level?
Would interest rate hikes (and the accompanying increase in unemployment) be worse than the disease itself?
Equally important: While the incorrect pricing of mortgage-backed securities played a central role in the 2008 crisis, there are now indications of an even stronger and more pervasive mispricing of assets related to climate change.
What should the Fed do about this?
Powell is not the man for the job.
Initially, he supported the deregulation agenda of former President Donald Trump and risked the financial health of our world.
And even now, he hesitates to take any action regarding the climate risk, although other central bankers worldwide have already declared this to be the central problem of the coming decades.
Powell would argue that climate issues are not part of the Fed's mandate, but he would be wrong.
It is part of the Fed's task to ensure financial stability, and there is no greater danger to financial stability than climate change.
The Fed is also responsible for approving mergers in the financial sector, and Powell's track record suggests that he has never experienced a bad merger.
The economy needs the opposite of this right now.
A glaring lack of competition and insufficient regulation are already allowing for excessive profits, reducing credit to small businesses, and giving dominant players more room to exploit others.
Some commentators give Powell credit for the Fed's response to the pandemic.
But every second-year student would have known that during a recession, you cannot tighten monetary policy and raise interest rates.
And as Simon Johnson from MIT has argued, Powell does not feel particularly strongly committed to full employment.
On the contrary: Powell's record as a member of the US Federal Reserve Board over the past decade has been marked by a series of flawed decisions on monetary policy, dating back to the "Taper Tantrum" in 2013.
Although many Fed observers insist that inequality is not the Fed's problem, it is a fact that the bank's policies have important distributional effects that cannot be ignored.
Just as an early hike in interest rates can strangle growth, a weak enforcement of the Community Reinvestment Act can allow for greater concentrations of market power.
And finally, the latest scandal over stock trading by senior Fed officials has eroded trust in the bank's leadership.
Powell's apparent lack of awareness of conflicts of interest, including his administration of some Fed programs in response to the pandemic, has been a concern of mine for a long time.
After four years of Trump weakening trust in US institutions, there is now a real risk that trust in the integrity of the central bank will suffer further.
No Fed official should need an ethics officer to decide when certain stock transactions would be improper.
The Fed is similar to the US Supreme Court in certain respects.
The Supreme Court is supposed to be above politics, but we have known since the Bush v. Gore case that this is not the case.
Trump has made it clear to anyone who had doubts.
The Fed is supposed to be independent, but Powell and Greenspan have clearly shown that this is not the case by following their party's deregulation agenda.
While the Federal Reserve Board makes important decisions that influence all aspects of the economy, power traditionally resides in the hands of the Federal Reserve Chairman – much more so than in the hands of the Chief Justice of the Supreme Court.
It is the Federal Reserve Chairman who decides what comes to a vote and which issues are postponed or pushed forward.
The climate issue is just one example of where it is extremely important who is at the head of the table.
The US needs a central bank that truly commits to ensuring a stable, fair, efficient, and competitive financial sector.
Those who believe we can rely on unbridled markets or that regulation has already gone too far lack foresight.
We need neither an ideologue like Greenspan nor a lawyer biased towards Wall Street like Powell.
What we need is someone with deep economic understanding who shares Biden's values and concerns about inflation and employment.
There are undoubtedly many people who meet these conditions.
But Biden doesn't have to look far to find someone who has already proven their capabilities.
Lael Brainard already sits on the Federal Reserve Board, where she has demonstrated her competence and gained the trust of the markets – without compromising her values.
Biden can have both: a central bank chief who preserves continuity and does not disrupt the markets, but who also shares his economic and social program.
